    description = 'A seminal work in Islamic revolutionary thought by Dr. Ali Shariati that systematically differentiates between authentic revolutionary Shiism (*Tashayyu'' Alawi*) and compromised institutional Shiism (*Tashayyu'' Safawi*). Originally delivered as a revolutionary manifesto at Hussainiya-e-Irshad in 1971, this ideological critique employs historical periodization and sociological analysis to demonstrate that authentic Shiism represents a revolutionary movement for justice rather than institutional religion serving state power. Shariati contrasts "Red Shiism" (the color of martyrdom and revolutionary sacrifice) with "Black Shiism" (the color of mourning and passive submission), arguing that Alawi Shiism from Ali ibn Abi Talib to the pre-Safavid period embodied resistance, justice, and revolutionary consciousness, while Safavid Shiism transformed religion into an instrument of political control and social oppression. The work establishes fundamental distinctions between the revolutionary scholar (*alim*) who maintains critical stance toward unjust power and the institutional cleric (*ruhani*) who collaborates with oppressive systems. Through rigorous analysis of religious movements versus religious institutions, Shariati provides theoretical foundations for Islamic liberation theology and revolutionary praxis. Essential reading for scholars of Islamic political thought, revolutionary ideology, Shia studies, liberation theology, and social movement theory, offering sophisticated frameworks for understanding religious authenticity, institutional co-optation, and the role of religion in social transformation and anti-colonial resistance.'

